1	\chapter{Genus of a smooth proper curve}
2	\label{chap:Genus}
3	
4	Throughout this chapter, $k$ denotes a field and $C$ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible scheme over $k$ of relative dimension $1$ — that is, $C \to \Spec k$ carries the typeclasses
5	\lstinline{[SmoothOfRelativeDimension 1 C.hom] [IsProper C.hom] [GeometricallyIrreducible C.hom]}.
6	We call such a $C$ a \emph{smooth proper curve over $k$}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}[Genus of a smooth proper curve]
11	  \label{def:genus}
12	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.genus}
13	  \leanok
14	  The \emph{genus} of a smooth proper curve $C$ over $k$ is the natural number
15	  \[
16	    g(C) \;=\; \dim_k H^1(C,\, \mathcal O_C),
17	  \]
18	  the $k$-dimension of the first sheaf-cohomology group of the structure sheaf of $C$.
19	\end{definition}
20	
21	Equivalent reformulations available once Riemann–Roch and Serre duality are formalised:
22	\begin{itemize}
23	  \item $g(C) = \dim_k H^0(C,\, \Omega^1_{C/k})$ (Serre duality).
24	  \item $g(C) = 1 - \chi(\mathcal O_C)$, where $\chi$ is the Euler characteristic.
25	  \item For a smooth projective curve over $\mathbb C$, $g(C)$ equals the topological genus of $C(\mathbb C)$.
26	\end{itemize}
27	Each of these requires Mathlib infrastructure that is currently absent (see Section \ref{sec:Genus_status}).
28	
29	\section{Mathlib gap}
30	\label{sec:Genus_status}
31	
32	The honest definition $\dim_k H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ requires:
33	
34	\begin{itemize}
35	  \item \textbf{Sheaf cohomology of quasi-coherent sheaves on schemes.} Mathlib has the abstract right-derived-functor machinery (\lstinline{CategoryTheory.Functor.RightDerived}) but no instantiation to $\Gamma(X, -) \colon \mathrm{QCoh}(X) \to \mathrm{Mod}_{\mathcal O_X(X)}$. Only étale/$\ell$-adic cohomology exists (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.EllAdicCohomology}), which is not what we need.
36	  \item \textbf{Finite-dimensionality of $H^i(C, \mathcal F)$ for coherent $\mathcal F$ on a proper scheme over a field} (Serre's theorem). Absent.
37	\end{itemize}
38	
39	\subsection{Discovery objective for this iteration}
40	
41	The prover should:
42	\begin{enumerate}
43	  \item Search Mathlib (\texttt{lean\_local\_search}, \texttt{lean\_leansearch}, \texttt{lean\_loogle}) for any existing API that computes $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ as a $k$-vector space, including via Čech cohomology, hypercoverings, or derived functors.
44	  \item Document the precise API gap in \lstinline{task_results/Genus.md}: which type or function would have to exist for the definition to typecheck, and what the closest existing Mathlib declaration is.
45	  \item \textbf{Do not} introduce a placeholder definition (such as \lstinline{genus := 0} or an opaque \lstinline{Classical.choice}); leave the \lstinline{sorry} in place rather than weakening the mathematical content.
46	  \item If — and only if — the cohomology API is found in Mathlib, fill the \lstinline{sorry} with the honest definition.
47	\end{enumerate}
48	
49	The phase-A roadmap in \texttt{STRATEGY.md} tracks how the missing cohomology API is to be built across subsequent iterations.
50

1	\chapter{The Jacobian as an abelian variety}
2	\label{chap:Jacobian}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ in the sense of Chapter \ref{chap:Genus}, with genus $g = g(C)$.
5	
6	\section{The Picard scheme and the Jacobian}
7	
8	% NOTE: Phase C — no Lean counterpart yet (Picard functor for schemes is absent
9	% from Mathlib b80f227; only `CommRing.Pic R` exists, for rings).
10	\begin{definition}[Picard functor]
11	  \label{def:Pic_functor}
12	  The \emph{Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the étale sheafification of the presheaf
13	  \[
14	    \underline{\Pic}_{C/k}\colon (\mathrm{Sch}/k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\to\; \mathrm{Ab},\qquad
15	    S \mapsto \Pic(C \times_k S) / \Pic(S).
16	  \]
17	\end{definition}
18	
19	% NOTE: Phase C — no Lean counterpart yet. This is the bundled representability
20	% theorem whose closure jointly unblocks `Jacobian`, `instGrpObj`, `instIsProper`,
21	% `instGeometricallyIrreducible`, and (with Phase A) `smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus`.
22	\begin{theorem}[Representability — Grothendieck FGA, Mumford \emph{Abelian Varieties} §III.13]
23	  \label{thm:Pic_representable}
24	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
25	  For a smooth proper geometrically connected curve $C$ over $k$, $\underline{\Pic}_{C/k}$ is representable by a smooth, locally finite-type group scheme $\Pic_{C/k}$ over $k$. Its connected component of the identity $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ is a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g$, hence an abelian variety.
26	\end{theorem}
27	
28	\begin{definition}[Jacobian]
29	  \label{def:Jacobian}
30	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian}
31	  \leanok
32	  \uses{thm:Pic_representable}
33	  The \emph{Jacobian} of $C$ is the abelian variety
34	  \[
35	    \Jac(C) \;=\; \Pic^0_{C/k},
36	  \]
37	  viewed as an object of $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$.
38	\end{definition}
39	
40	\section{Group scheme structure and abelian-variety properties}
41	
42	\begin{theorem}[Group object structure]
43	  \label{thm:Jacobian_grpObj}
44	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGrpObj}
45	  \leanok
46	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
47	  $\Jac(C)$ carries a canonical group-object structure in $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$, induced from tensor product of line bundles on $C$.
48	\end{theorem}
49	
50	\begin{theorem}[Smoothness and dimension]
51	  \label{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus}
52	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus}
53	  \leanok
54	  \uses{def:Jacobian, def:genus}
55	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $g(C)$.
56	\end{theorem}
57	
58	\begin{theorem}[Properness]
59	  \label{thm:Jacobian_proper}
60	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instIsProper}
61	  \leanok
62	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
63	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is proper.
64	\end{theorem}
65	
66	\begin{theorem}[Geometric irreducibility]
67	  \label{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred}
68	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGeometricallyIrreducible}
69	  \leanok
70	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
71	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is geometrically irreducible.
72	\end{theorem}
73	
74	\noindent All four properties are part of the conclusion of Theorem \ref{thm:Pic_representable}: once $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ is constructed as an abelian scheme of dimension $g(C)$, smoothness, properness and geometric irreducibility hold by construction.
75	
76	\subsection{Sanity check in low genus}
77	
78	\begin{itemize}
79	  \item $g = 0$: Then $\Pic^0_{C/k} = \Spec k$, the trivial group scheme; $\Jac(\mathbb P^1_k) = \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $0 = g$. The terminal object of $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$ already carries \lstinline{GrpObj} via \lstinline{instTensorUnit}.
80	  \item $g = 1$: Then $\Jac(C) \cong C$ once a $k$-rational point on $C$ is fixed; $C$ is itself an abelian variety.
81	  \item $g \ge 2$: $\Jac(C)$ is a non-trivial $g$-dimensional abelian variety, never isomorphic to $C$ as a scheme.
82	\end{itemize}
83	
84	\section{Mathlib gap}
85	
86	The Picard scheme is absent from Mathlib b80f227. Mathlib has only \lstinline{CommRing.Pic R} (the Picard group of a commutative ring) and the abstract \lstinline{GrpObj} machinery. Constructing \lstinline{Jacobian C} therefore requires building, inside this project:
87	
88	\begin{itemize}
89	  \item the Picard functor (Definition \ref{def:Pic_functor}) — needs a global \lstinline{Scheme.Pic} for schemes;
90	  \item étale sheafification of group-valued functors on $\mathrm{Sch}/k$;
91	  \item representability for the curve case (Theorem \ref{thm:Pic_representable});
92	  \item the connected-component-of-identity construction for group schemes locally of finite type.
93	\end{itemize}
94	
95	These are mapped to Phase C of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
96	
97	\subsection{Discovery objective for this iteration}
98	
99	The prover should:
100	\begin{enumerate}
101	  \item Verify that no Picard-scheme construction exists in Mathlib (search for \lstinline{Picard}, \lstinline{Pic}, \lstinline{LineBundle}, \lstinline{InvertibleSheaf}, \lstinline{InvertibleModule} inside the algebraic-geometry namespace).
102	  \item For each of the five protected declarations in \lstinline{Jacobian.lean}, document in \lstinline{task_results/Jacobian.md} the smallest helper lemma whose existence in Mathlib would make that declaration provable in $\le 20$ lines.
103	  \item \textbf{Do not} introduce ad-hoc placeholder definitions (e.g. \lstinline{Jacobian C := 𝟙_ (Over (Spec (.of k)))}, which would only satisfy the four instances when $g(C) = 0$ and is therefore mathematically wrong).
104	\end{enumerate}
105

1	\chapter{The Abel--Jacobi map}
2	\label{chap:AbelJacobi}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ as in Chapter \ref{chap:Genus}, and let $\Jac(C)$ be its Jacobian (Definition \ref{def:Jacobian}).
5	
6	\section{Definition}
7	
8	\begin{definition}[Abel--Jacobi map]
9	  \label{def:ofCurve}
10	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.ofCurve}
11	  \leanok
12	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
13	  Given a $k$-rational point $P\colon \Spec k \to C$ — equivalently, a morphism $P\colon \mathbf 1 \to C$ in $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$ — the \emph{Abel--Jacobi map} is the $k$-morphism
14	  \[
15	    \alpha_P\colon C \;\longrightarrow\; \Jac(C),\qquad Q \;\longmapsto\; [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)].
16	  \]
17	  Functorially, it is the morphism in $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$ induced by the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$ via the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
18	\end{definition}
19	
20	\section{Pointed property}
21	
22	\begin{lemma}[$\alpha_P$ sends $P$ to $0$]
23	  \label{lem:comp_ofCurve}
24	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.comp_ofCurve}
25	  \leanok
26	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
27	  $P \;\circ\; \alpha_P \;=\; \eta\bigl[\Jac(C)\bigr]$, where $\eta[\Jac(C)]$ is the identity element of the group scheme $\Jac(C)$.
28	\end{lemma}
29	
30	\begin{proof}
31	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
32	  At the level of $k$-points: $\alpha_P(P) = [\mathcal O_C(P - P)] = [\mathcal O_C] = 0$. Globally: by construction, $\alpha_P$ is the morphism classifying the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$; restricting to the section $(P, \mathrm{id})$ gives the trivial line bundle, hence the zero point of $\Pic^0$.
33	\end{proof}
34	
35	\section{Universal (Albanese) property}
36	
37	\begin{theorem}[Albanese property of the Jacobian]
38	  \label{thm:exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
39	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
40	  \leanok
41	  \uses{def:ofCurve, lem:comp_ofCurve}
42	  Let $A$ be an abelian variety over $k$ — i.e.\ $A \in \textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$ with \lstinline{[Smooth A.hom] [IsProper A.hom] [GrpObj A] [GeometricallyIrreducible A.hom]}. For every pointed morphism $f\colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta[A]$, there exists a unique group-scheme morphism $g\colon \Jac(C) \to A$ such that $f = g \circ \alpha_P$.
43	  \[
44	  \begin{array}{ccc}
45	    C & \stackrel{f}{\longrightarrow} & A \\
46	    {\scriptstyle\alpha_P} \downarrow & \nearrow {\scriptstyle\exists ! g} & \\
47	    \Jac(C) & &
48	  \end{array}
49	  \]
50	\end{theorem}
51	
52	\begin{proof}
53	  \uses{thm:Pic_representable}
54	  \emph{Existence.} The map $f\colon C \to A$ pointed at $P$ is classified, via the Picard-functoriality of $A$, by a line bundle on $C \times A^\vee$ (where $A^\vee$ is the dual abelian variety), normalised so that its restriction along $\{P\}\times A^\vee$ is trivial. By the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, this line bundle yields a $k$-morphism $A^\vee \to \Pic^0_{C/k} = \Jac(C)$; dualising back gives $g\colon \Jac(C) \to A$ with $g \circ \alpha_P = f$.
55	
56	  \emph{Uniqueness.} If $g_1, g_2\colon \Jac(C) \to A$ both satisfy $g_i \circ \alpha_P = f$, then $g_1 - g_2\colon \Jac(C) \to A$ vanishes on the image of $\alpha_P$. The image of $\alpha_P$ generates $\Jac(C)$ as a group scheme (a standard fact: the Abel--Jacobi morphism is generically finite onto its image and the symmetric power $C^{(g)}$ surjects onto $\Jac(C)$). Combined with the rigidity theorem for morphisms between abelian varieties (Mumford, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, §4 Theorem 1: a morphism of abelian varieties vanishing on a non-empty open subset is zero), this forces $g_1 = g_2$.
57	\end{proof}
58	
59	\section{Mathlib gap}
60	
61	The Albanese property requires:
62	\begin{itemize}
63	  \item the rigidity theorem for morphisms between abelian varieties (Mumford §4) — \emph{not} in Mathlib, but provable from \lstinline{Mathlib/AlgebraicGeometry/Group/Abelian.lean} plus the rigidity lemma for proper morphisms over an irreducible base;
64	  \item generation of $\Jac(C)$ by the image of $\alpha_P$ — requires symmetric powers of curves and the surjectivity $C^{(g)} \twoheadrightarrow \Jac(C)$;
65	  \item dual abelian varieties and biduality — currently absent.
66	\end{itemize}
67	
68	These are mapped to Phase E of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
69	
70	\subsection{Discovery objective for this iteration}
71	
72	The prover should:
73	\begin{enumerate}
74	  \item Confirm that none of \lstinline{ofCurve}, \lstinline{comp_ofCurve}, \lstinline{exists_unique_ofCurve_comp} can be filled without first defining \lstinline{Jacobian C} (Chapter \ref{chap:Jacobian}).
75	  \item Document in \lstinline{task_results/AbelJacobi.md} which of the three sorries would become provable from a working \lstinline{Jacobian} via what specific helper lemmas (e.g.\ \enquote{rigidity for morphisms of abelian varieties} as a standalone declaration).
76	  \item \textbf{Do not} introduce a placeholder \lstinline{ofCurve} (such as the constant map to the identity) — this would make \lstinline{exists_unique_ofCurve_comp} false in genus $\ge 1$.
77	\end{enumerate}
